Methods: Denominator is NYC DOHMH population estimates, modified from US Census Bureau intercensal population estimates, updated 2014. The death events reported are based on certificates filed with the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene (DOHMH) for vital events occurring in or in-route to New York City, regardless of individual residency status, in a particular year. Any events registered after file closure (typically occurring within 5 months of year-end) are excluded from this report. Such late registrations are rare. Data are age-adjusted to the US 2000 standard population.

Source: Source: California Electronic Death Registration System (CA-EDRS), as of April 1, 2016.  Includes immediate cause of death and contributing causes of death.   Includes records for which Long Beach was recorded on the death certificate as the decedents city of residence.  Duplicate records due to revisions to the death certificate are not included.  ICD-10 codes were not included in the dataset; algorithms were written to match key words from cause of death to the corresponding ICD-10 diagnosis.
Notes: Deaths for which cause was listed as deferred for review by a coroner or for which cause was missing are not included.  Counts from which rates are derived are subject to change due to late reporting or revisions to the cause of death.

Methods: Denominator is NYC DOHMH population estimates, modified from US Census Bureau intercensal population estimates, updated 2014. The death events reported are based on certificates filed with the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene (DOHMH) for vital events occurring in or in-route to New York City, regardless of individual residency status, in a particular year. Any events registered after file closure (typically occurring within 5 months of year-end) are excluded from this report. Such late registrations are rare. Data are age-adjusted to the US 2000 standard population.

ICD-10 codes were not included in the dataset; algorithms were written to match key words from cause of death to the corresponding ICD-10 diagnosis.
Notes: Deaths for which cause was listed as deferred for review by a coroner or for which cause was missing are not included.  Counts from which rates are derived are subject to change due to late reporting or revisions to the cause of death.

BCHC Requested Methodology: All deaths per 100,000 population using 2010 US Census figures, age adjusted to the year 2000 standard population
Source: NYC DOHMH Bureau of Vital Statistics
Methods: Denominator is NYC DOHMH population estimates, modified from US Census Bureau intercensal population estimates, updated 2014. The death events reported are based on certificates filed with the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene (DOHMH) for vital events occurring in or in-route to New York City, regardless of individual residency status, in a particular year. Any events registered after file closure (typically occurring within 5 months of year-end) are excluded from this report. Such late registrations are rare. Data are age-adjusted to the US 2000 standard population.

Any events registered after file closure (typically occurring within 5 months of year-end) are excluded from this report. Such late registrations are rare. Data are age-adjusted to the US 2000 standard population.

Source: Source: California Electronic Death Registration System (CA-EDRS), as of April 1, 2016.  Includes immediate cause of death and contributing causes of death.   Includes records for which Long Beach was recorded on the death certificate as the decedents city of residence.  Duplicate records due to revisions to the death certificate are not included.  ICD-10 codes were not included in the dataset; algorithms were written to match key words from cause of death to the corresponding ICD-10 diagnosis.
Notes: Deaths for which cause was listed as deferred for review by a coroner or for which cause was missing are not included.  Counts from which rates are derived are subject to change due to late reporting or revisions to the cause of death.
